label chapter24:

    # [Scene: Seawall Construction Site | Morning]

    scene bg ch14_4e48f4_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rhythmic thump of a pile-driver; a distant sheriff’s radio; the hollow echo of men moving forms; gulls keening above.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft ascending strings — quiet, hopeful, like breath held and then released]
    "You arrive with the aftertaste of the Beacon still on your tongue: meeting minutes folded into your jacket pocket, halting handshakes and the smell of coffee that had kept the night awake. Whether you came straight"
    "from the community workshop or from the plaza where banners were sung into place, the town’s choice is visible here in concrete and motion."
    "The seawall is not a graceful thing. It is brutal, honest, and fast — poured by crews who work like they know time is a rising tide. The sound of the pile-driver makes your ribs vibrate;"
    "the sea sprays salt across your face and the air smells of wet cement and diesel and new wood. You run a thumb along the spine of your field notebook, feeling the worn lighthouse sticker. The"
    "sticker is small against the industry of the wall, but it has survived worse weather than your own hesitations."
    "Elias 'Eli' Navarro steps up beside you, boots scuffed in the same line of work. He has a tape measure slung around his neck and a smudge of concrete on his knuckle. His eyes find yours,"
    "then the line of the wall, then the row of storefronts. Something unreadable crosses his face for a beat — part relief, part calculation."

    "Elias 'Eli' Navarro" "They've accelerated Phase One. The contractors promised a week, then shaved three days off the schedule. Hal's crew is overseeing the stress loads, but the teams are moving around the clock."
    show amara_vale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amara_vale "So speed won."

    "Elias 'Eli' Navarro" "Speed and money, and some hard calls. They took out the low front of the promenade to pour the base. A few shopfronts were in the way.' (He watches your reaction.) 'We put the rehousing fund in the contract. Oversight clauses. A community monitor on every shift."
    "You hold the words like a ledger. Rehousing fund. Oversight clauses. They read like hope in legalese but also like a bandage stretched over a wound. Your chest tightens with the memory of the plaza —"
    "Rosa's voice, Miriam's megaphone, Hal's hands on the prototype. You know what the clauses promise, and you know what is already gone."
    hide amara_vale

    scene bg ch14_4e48f4_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Conversation lowers; a nearby jackhammer pauses as people listen]
    "Marco Voss approaches with a smile that is all polished conviction."
    show marco_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marco_voss "Amara. Eli. The wall looks good in morning light, doesn't it? Solid work.' (He gestures toward the rising face.) 'Faster than anyone predicted. We bought the crews that could do it."
    show amara_vale at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amara_vale "We chose speed, Marco."
    "Marco Voss: (tilting his head) 'We chose lives. We chose a line that keeps the water out. Heritage matters — I understand that — but losing a few storefront fronts is not the same as losing everyone when the next surge comes.'"
    "His words are smooth; your stomach tightens because they are true and because they are partial. You sense the calculus that colored each clause in the contract: what can be preserved, what must be given up, and who decides that ledger."

    menu:
        "Walk the storefronts with Rosa":
            "You move down the row with Rosa at your side, fingers trailing the rough plywood where a pastry window used to glint. She points out a framed menu now soaked under plastic and describes the landlord who cried the day permits came through — small griefs that make the loss human."
        "Stand on the seawall with Elias 'Eli' Navarro":
            "You climb the temporary steps to the top of the wall with Elias 'Eli' Navarro. From there the harbor looks different: the town feels contained and resilient, the houses tucked behind a gray spine. Elias 'Eli' Navarro lays a hand on the concrete as if testing its heartbeat and says quietly, 'It held when it counted.'"

    # --- merge ---
    "Rosa Kwan comes into the small circle you’ve made. Her knit cap is the color of sunrise and dusted with concrete like confetti. She speaks before you can organize your protest or praise."
    "Rosa Kwan: (soft, direct) 'The bakery lost its face. Karim's place — he had his whole life in that front. We have vouchers. We have the rehousing endowment moving. But it still feels like someone took a face off the town and called it a new smile.'"

    amara_vale "We will make it right."
    "Elias 'Eli' Navarro: (quietly, to you) 'We put the clause for tenant relocation in the first tranche. Marco signed the escrow. He pushed for speed in exchange. We protected the money with a stoppage clause if payrolls weren't met.'"
    "Your mind runs down a list of what those protections mean in practice. It means emergency leases paid. It means temporary storefronts on the elevated promenade. It means stimulus microgrants so small businesses can re-open. It means months at least of coordination and a thousand small kindnesses."
    "Marco Voss: (interjecting) 'And we've scheduled community oversight every twelve hours, with a rotating monitor appointed by your council. The oversight is funded indefinitely — not just for the build, but for maintenance. This wall is a start. We'll combine municipal funding and private capital for the rest.'"
    "You look at Marco. The sunlight on his watch is sharp. He offers the kinds of promises that can and will be audited. You feel the typical friction — his solution is fast, scalable, and expensive"
    "in ways that ask for local sacrifice. But the first storm to test the wall is a storm you cannot afford to dismiss."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A low rolling thunder, far at first, like the ocean breathing in.]
    hide marco_voss
    hide amara_vale

    scene bg ch14_4e48f4_3 at full_bg
    "The town does not wait for perfect debate. The sea is not patient with theory. Within ten days of the last bolt of concrete setting, a storm with teeth rolls in from the southwest. You stand"
    "on the crest of the promenade with Elias 'Eli' Navarro and Rosa, hands tucked into your jacket, the air full of wet grit and the piping of emergency channels."
    show amara_vale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amara_vale "This is the part that would make or break us. If it holds, the argument for speed is a human testimony. If it fails, we will have to answer the people who trusted us."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind picks up; the seawall takes the first hit — a stomach-sink whoomph as water pounds against treated concrete. Spray arcs over the parapet and for a breath your heart flutters at the sound of surge on stone.]
    "Elias 'Eli' Navarro: (over the wind, shouting) 'Sensors are stable! Stress numbers are within the modeled range! Hal was right about the foundations.'"
    "You almost laugh out loud because relief is sudden and sharp and almost ashamedly bright. A woman on the promenade cries out as water sluices down a service alley but is channeled away into catchment basins instead of flooding the basement where Karim once proofed pastries."
    "Rosa Kwan: (calling) 'They kept the people in their homes this time. We did that.'"
    "Marco Voss arrives, soaked at the sleeves but smiling like a man who has banked on a good outcome."
    show marco_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marco_voss "You did the hard thing — you chose a line and you stuck to it. The town can use that. There will be time to rebuild the faces we lost. There will be funds."
    "Amara Vale [internal]: The wall has held. Lives were spared. The immediate crisis is averted. There is a bright ribbon of hope threading through grief. You taste salt and something like triumph, tempered by the knowledge that reputations and livelihoods still need tending."

    menu:
        "Help organize temporary shop spaces":
            "You kneel with Rosa by the empty doorway and start sketching a plan for a pop-up stall on a raised platform, already calling two volunteers from your list. The momentum of your hands makes the plan feel real."
        "Sit with Elias 'Eli' Navarro and catalogue sensor data":
            "You sit with Elias 'Eli' Navarro under a tarp and begin reading the sensor readouts aloud. Each stable number is a small victory; each spike is noted and scheduled for follow-up."
        "Confront Marco Voss about long-term accountability":
            "You corner Marco Voss near the equipment shed and press him on enforcement. He answers with a careful, corporate patience — promises of audits and an open channel — but you leave with his words still sashaying between reassurance and vagueness."

    # --- merge ---
    "The aftermath is not triumphal; it is pragmatic. Volunteers sweep boards. A temporary sign hangs where Karim's bakery front once smiled: 'Karim will return — Temporary Location: 3rd St. Market Stall.' Rehousing vans move slowly, not"
    "like eviction but like careful relocation. Oversight committees form and meet under the Beacon's low-slung glass. The language of law sits beside the language of glue and song."
    "You watch people do the work — the real repair is not in contracts but in the small acts. A teenage volunteer boots mud from a florist's rug. Hal checks bolt tensions with an older, delighted"
    "grin. Rosa hands out hot tea in paper cups, her hands flour-dusted but warm. Elias 'Eli' Navarro counts out volunteer shifts on his wristband, the blue-gray of his eyes steady."
    "Elias 'Eli' Navarro: (reaching for your hand, briefly) 'We saved people today. We'll pay for what we lost. We'll make sure no one is left without a roof while they rebuild.'"

    amara_vale "You have done what you could and what you could not. There will be more storms. There will be more choices. But today — today a wall held. Today that mattered."
    hide amara_vale
    hide marco_voss

    scene bg ch14_4e48f4_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Roseate ascending strings swell — warm, steady, carrying the moment into a held chord]
    "You take a breath that is both grief and gratitude. You fold a piece of wet paper — a repair estimate with Marco's stamped initials — and tuck it into your notebook. You think of Karim's"
    "laugh, the thrumming machine, Hal’s steady hands, Elias 'Eli' Navarro's practical kindness, Rosa’s stubborn warmth. The town is altered. It is also alive."
    # [Page-Turn Moment]
    "You walk the new promenade at dusk, fingertips grazing the rail. The lamps hum; the banners that once called for resistance now flutter with hand-painted additions — names of volunteers, dates of meetings, a small painted"
    "pastry where Karim’s window used to be. You feel the town's breath steady as if learning a new pattern. There is much to do: appeals to shepherd through councils, a schedule for maintenance, a long list"
    "of displaced people to house with dignity. But the immediate danger has receded like a tide and left work to be done on firm ground."
    "You close your notebook and look at the harbor — at the seawall, at the softened line of rooftops behind it — and for the first time in a long time you feel the future as something you can touch and shape rather than only fear."

    scene bg ch14_4e48f4_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm chord holds, then softens to a single sustained note]

    scene bg ch14_4e48f4_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter28
